Herring spawn surveys have been conducted throughout the B.C. coast beginning in the 1930s.
Prior to 1988, spawn surveys were conducted from the surface either by walking the beach at low tide or using a drag from a skiff to estimate the shoreline length and width of spawn.
Beginning in 1988, herring spawn surveys using SCUBA methods were introduced and were implemented coastwide within a couple of years, initially being conducted by DFO staff and eventually through contract divers hired through the test fishery program.
Prior to the 2006 Larocque ruling the test fishery program was funded through an allocation of fish, and from 2007-2014 this data collection program has been funded by DFO.
In 2014, dive surveys were conducted in all major and minor assessment regions.

Both survey methods (surface or dive) involve collecting information on spawn length (parallel to shore), spawn width (perpendicular to shore), and number of egg layers by vegetation type.
These data are used to calculate egg densities per spawning bed, with the ultimate goal of estimating spawning biomass, following the methods of Schweigert et al. (2001).
Estimates of spawn length, spawn width, and average number of egg layers are presented in Appendix B for all major stock areas.

For the purposes of stock assessment, spawn survey data are represented as two independent indices: (1) surface survey index from 1951--1987 and (2) dive survey index from 1988--\Sexpr{assess.yr}.
Spawn indices are an output of the Herring Stock Assessment Database, in units of metric tonnes of herring spawning biomass.
Time series of spawn index by major stock area, from 1951--1987 (surface observations) and 1988--\Sexpr{assess.yr} (dive observations) are summarized in Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}.
It is worth noting that since 1988, some early and late season surface surveys have been conducted, representing a small proportion of total spawn survey in a given area (Appendix XX).
These surface data were processed so that their average width estimates are in a comparable format to those from dive survey data and surface survey average width estimates were rolled up with dive survey estimates.
In 3 of the major stock areas (HG, PRD and CC), numeric estimates of spawning biomass (spawn index values) decreased in 2014 over 2013.
In the other 2 stock areas (SOG and WCVI), numeric estimates of spawning biomass (spawn index values) increased in 2014 over 2013.
Execution of the 2014 spawn survey followed all standard protocols as described in the 2013 version of the 
\href{http://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/species-especes/pelagic-pelagique/herring-hareng/hertags/pdf/SurveyManual.pdf}{herring spawn survey manual}
and there were no in-season or post-season concerns raised by the HCRS (contractor) or the DFO Area Managers that would raise concern around the quality of spawn survey data collected this season.

\subsubsection{Proportion-at-age and catch-at-age}

Observed proportions-at-age from Gear 2 biological samples (roe seine, seine test, SOK, where available) by stock area are summarized in Figure \ref{figProportionAge}.
%Trends in proportion-at-age by Gear 1 and Gear 3 are included in Appendix XX.
Adjustments made in analytical procedures included weighting Area 8 biological samples by their average relative contribution over the past 20 years (7\%), due to concerns that data acquired and used for the Central Coast area resulted from an uncommonly high number of samples (6 of 13) that were collected from Statistical Area 8 (which is historically an unfished area with consistently smaller (age 2) fish), Area 8; and, removing WCVI Statistical Area 24 samples, because it was determined that they were not representative.

We also use the catch-at-age data for a catch curve analysis (Chapman and Robson, 1960) for ages 6--10.
Here we determine static $Z_\mli{stat}$ from the traditional catch curve method (the slope of the log of catches at age) and also dynamically as $Z_\mli{dyn}=log(\sum P6-9, t\sum P7-10, t+1)$.
Our main motivation for doing so was to check if the apparent time-varying natural mortality estimated by the assessment model could be confirmed using the data alone, and also to address some concerns expressed by participants at last year's review meeting about the validity of the assessment model estimating time-varying natural mortality ($M$).
While the reliability of the catch curve method can be diminished by variable recruitment, time-varying $M$ and other factors, they have been shown to capture the general magnitude of the total mortality Z, in other fish stocks (Allen 1997, Thorson and Prager 2011).

The assessment model's estimates of $Z$ are likely more reliable than either static or dynamic catch curve estimates because it explicitly accounts for variable recruitment and $F$ (that will distort catch curve estimates of $Z$ if they are variable).
Understanding that the absolute value of $Z$ estimates would be incorrect with catch curve analyses, one key thing that we hoped to examine was if $Z$s estimated by the catch curve methods followed a similar pattern to ISCAM's estimates of $Z$ particularly for HG, CC and WCVI stock areas where after fishing ceased the only other source of changes in Z would be $M$.
We plot the catch curve estimates of $Z$ alone with those output from the assessment model for comparison in Figure XX (red and green, and black lines, respectively).

$Z_\mli{dyn}$ does track the trends estimated using the assessment model (Figure 8, red), with the running average in $Z\mli{dyn}$ showing the same pattern as the increasing trends in $M$ estimated by the assessment model from the early 1990s-2008 in the CC, HG and WCVI.
In the SOG, $Z_\mli{dyn}$ also tracked the recent declines in $Z$.
Notwithstanding the difference in the absolute value of $Z$ between the catch curve estimates and the assessment model, the catch curve analysis does support the assessment model's assumption that $M$ is time-varying in capturing similar patterns to the assessment model in the closed areas, when the only component of $Z$ that could have been in effect was $M$.

