\subsubsection{Data summaries for major SARs}

We provide a brief description of input data to the assessment model for each of the major \Sexpr{fish.name} SARs.

\textbf{Haida Gwaii}

The survey index declined in 2014 from approximately 16 kilo tonnes (kt) in 2013 to 10.6 kt (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
Relative to 2013, changes in mean weight at age depended on age.
Mean weight at age for age 2, 5, 6 fish increased a minimum of 8\% to a maximum of approximately 15\% (for age 2) (Figure \ref{figWeightAge}).
While the trajectory for size at age has generally been upward since 2011, the ratio of the 2014 mean weight at age to the 1951-2014 mean is between 66 and 98\%.
The proportions at age were dominated by age 4 fish (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).
There were 12 seine-test vessel samples (each of approximately 100 fish) used to calculate mean weight at age and proportions at age data in 2014 (Appendix \ref{chap:input}).

\textbf{Prince Rupert District}

The survey index declined from 25.7 kt in 2013 to 17.1 kt in 2014 (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
There were 15 seine-caught samples (excludes the gillnet fishery samples, Appendix \ref{chap:input}) available for determining the weight at age and proportions at age in 2014 (Figures \ref{figWeightAge}, and \ref{figProportionAge}, respectively).
Weight at age increased for 2 and 4 year old fish by approximately 25\% (not shown) but declined for age 3 fish; for ages 5-10, weight at age did not change by more than 5\%.
The current weight at age for all age classes is between 78-98\% of the 1951-2014 means.
The proportions at age were dominated by age 4 fish from the 2011 cohort (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).

\textbf{Central Coast}

The spawn survey index declined from 20.4 kt to 13.21 kt, (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
There were 13 seine-caught samples (excludes the gillnet fishery samples, Appendix \ref{chap:input}) available for determining the weight at age and proportions at age in 2014 but there was concern that these included an uncommonly high number of samples collected from Statistical Area 8, which is historically an unfished area with consistently smaller (age 2) fish (DFO 2015).
As a result, Area 8 biological samples were weighted by their average relative contribution over the past 20 years (7\%) in the final analysis (Figure XX, XX).
Mean weight at age declined for all age classes:  for age 2,4,5,6,8 fish, the declines were less than 10\% but for age 3 and 9 fish the declines were 18 and 28\% respectively.
The 2014 weights at age are between 56 and 91\% of the long term (1951-2014) averages.
As in HG, PRD and CC areas, the age composition data were dominated by age 4 fish (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).

\textbf{Strait of Georgia}

The spawn survey index increased from 84 kt in 2013 to 120 kt (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
There were 32 seine-caught samples (roe season only, Appendix \ref{chap:input}) available for determining the weight at age and proportions at age in 2014 (Figures \ref{figWeightAge}, \& \ref{figProportionAge}, respectively).
Relative to 2013, weight at age for age 2 and age 10 fish declined by 33 and 9\% respectively, but otherwise all weight at age increased for age 3-9 fish by 1-14\%.
The 2014 weights at age are between 78 and 99\% of the long term (1951-2014) averages.
Unlike the other major stock areas the age composition data was dominated by several age classes (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).

\textbf{West Coast of Vancouver Island}

The spawn survey index increased from 12.3 in 2013 to 13.9 kt (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
The current spawn survey index is at approximately 30\% of the maximum survey biomass observed in the dive survey time series.
There were 4 seine-caught samples for determining the weight at age and proportions at age in 2014 but there was concern that a Statistical Area 24 sample was not representative and was removed from the analysis (DFO 2015).
Therefore the number of samples underlying the mean weight at age data for the WCVI is very small (n=3), preceded by n=5 in 2013, as compared with n=10, 14, 23, 22, and 12 in years 2012-2008, respectively (Appendix\ref{chap:input}).
Save age 2 fish, the observed mean weight at age increased, or remained the same for all age classes (Figure \ref{figWeightAge}, based on the 4 seine-test fishery samples collected in 2014).
The observed proportions at age were dominated by age 3 fish (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).
The 2014 weights at age are between 78 and 95\% of the long term (1951-2014) averages.

\subsection{STATISTICAL CATCH-AT-AGE MODEL}

This assessment reports a base case of a catch-age model that is fitted to three sources of data: commercial catch, spawn survey biomass index, and proportions-at-age.
Two alternate management procedures are also explored (Section XX).
The assessment depends primarily upon the spawn survey biomass index (surface: 1951 - 1987, dive: 1988 - 2014) for information on the scale of the major herring stocks.
Fishery and seine test fishery age-composition data (1951-2014) are combined for each of the three gear types, contributing to the assessment model's ability to resolve strong and weak cohorts, and to forecast recruitment. 

The assessment uses Bayesian methods to incorporate prior information and integrate over parameter uncertainty to provide results that can be probabilistically interpreted.
The exploration of uncertainty is not limited to parameter uncertainty as structural uncertainty is investigated through retrospective analyses (Section XX).

\subsubsection{Changes from the 2013 assessment}

The assessment model was compiled using AD Model Builder (ADMB) version 11.1, released May 10, 2013.
This version included a number of improvements to algorithms and libraries, and the correction of defects (bugs).
A defect (bug fix) was also made to catch equations within the Baranov.cxx file.
These changes are considered regular year-to-year updates and lead to slight differences in model estimates and projections when comparing Base\_2013 runs (Section XX) with results captured in the September 2013 assessment document.

Adjustments made in analytical procedures included weighting Area 8 biological samples by their average relative contribution over the past 20 years (7\%), due to concerns that data acquired and used for the Central Coast area resulted from an uncommonly high number of samples (6 of 13) that were collected from Statistical Area 8 (which is historically an unfished area with consistently smaller (age 2) fish), Area 8; and, removing WCVI Statistical Area 24 samples, because it was determined that they were not representative.

\subsubsection{Model description}

A Bayesian statistical catch-at-age model was applied to assess each of the \Sexpr{length(allRegions$major)} \Sexpr{fish.name} major SARs separately.
The model is based on the Integrated Statistical Catch Age Model (iSCAM) framework \citep{martell2011}.
Full model details are provided in Appendix \ref{chap:equations}.

Marginal posterior distributions for estimated model parameters were constructed using the AD Model Builder built in Metropolis-Hastings algorithm (Fournier et al., 2012).
For each major assessment area, a systematic sample of 5,000 points were taken from a chain of length 5,000,000, intended to represent a random sample from the marginal posterior distribution.
These analytical steps (Bayesian methods) are the same as were applied in September 2011 (Martell et al. 2012), September 2012 (Cleary et al. working paper; DFO 2012b), and September 2013 (Cleary et al. working paper; DFO 2014) and are consistent with previous years' assessments using HCAM (Cleary and Schweigert 2012; Schweigert et al. 2009).
This procedure integrates over the full range of uncertainty producing a posterior distribution for each parameter estimated in the model. Then, these samples are used to construct marginal distributions for derived quantities (e.g., SB0).
See Appendix XX for technical description of model and applications.
Priority areas of research identified during past CSAS meetings (2011-2013) are summarized in Appendix XX.

