\textbf{Haida Gwaii}

The base case assessment estimates a decline in spawning stock biomass in 2014, relative to 2013 and a correspondingly lower stock status relative to the unfished state.
Recall that the data indicate a lower spawn survey biomass estimate in 2014, relatively minor increases in weight at age and age composition that is dominated by a single cohort of age-4 fish (Figure \ref{figProportionAge}).
In order to fit these observations, the model estimates that the last large recruitment event, in 2012, has been followed by relative small recruitments in 2013 and 2014 (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2HG}).
While estimates of current natural mortality remain highly uncertain, there is a recent increase in the median (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2HG}).
With no apparent recruitment entering the spawning population in 2014 and similar natural mortality, the model estimates that current spawning stock biomass has declined from 2013 (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2HG}) with a median and 90\% credibility intervals of 23 kt (12, 44) tonnes (Table XX) and lower depletion levels in 2014 than in 2013 (Figure XX), estimated to be 0.67 (0.35, 1.25) (Table XX).

\textbf{Prince Rupert District}

The base case assessment estimates relatively small declines in spawning stock biomass in 2014 (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2PRD}).
The survey data indicate declines of approximately 35\% - however the model over-fits the most recent observation (Appendix XX).
The model's historical reconstructions using the full set of age-composition data of the predicted survey biomass have not estimated the same, occasionally very large changes in the index: for example the decline from 2005 from 28 kt to 10 kt 2004 or from 12 kt to 28kt between 2009 and 2010; so that the model's estimate of the survey variance is relatively high (at the MPD, sigma=0.46).
As it was in HG, the model estimates that the last large recruitment event was in 2012 and that there is no evidence for large 2013 or 2014 cohorts (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2PRD}, Table XX).
Natural mortality is estimated to be highly uncertain, with trajectories that are a range of decreasing, stable, and increasing (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2PRD}).
The base case estimates that current median (90\% credibility intervals) spawning stock biomass is 29 (16, 51) kt (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2PRD}, Table XX) and depletion levels in 2014 than in 2013 (Figure XX), estimated to be 0.46 (0.23, 84) (Table XX).

\textbf{Central Coast}

Interpreting the model fits to the CC data is complex.
The age composition data show an apparent increase in the proportions of age 2 fish since 2013 (increasing from 2\% in 2013 to 14\% in 2014).
The spawn survey data indicate a decline in the spawning biomass index between 2013 and 2014 - but - this pattern is not born out in the model's reconstructions.
This is the case because while the model fits the most recent survey biomass exactly, it under-fits the 2013 spawn survey observation on order to fit the 2014 spawn survey index (Appendix \ref{chap:input}).
Paradoxically, the model therefore estimates a recent trajectory of only a slight decrease in median spawning stock biomass (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2CC}) but that is a large adjustment to spawning stock biomass given last year's positive retrospective error (Section XX).
The 2014 spawning stock biomass and depletion levels estimated to be 24 (14,41) kt and 0.41 (0.24,67), respectively whereas spawning stock biomass and depletion estimates for 2013 were 29 (18,49) kt and 0.48 (0.29,0.78), respectively (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2CC}, Table XX).

\textbf{Strait of Georgia}

The model fits the recent spawn survey index and age composition data (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2SoG}) by estimating both relatively large recent recruitments (2010 particularly) and improved survival of through natural mortality of all cohorts (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2SoG}, Table XX).
The model fits recent increasing trends in spawn survey index (Appendix \ref{chap:input}) and estimates recent spawning stock biomass trajectory that has been increasing since 2010 (Figure \ref{figSpawnIndex}).
The current spawning stock biomass and depletion levels are 186 (116, 289) kt and 1.31 (0.84, 1.96) respectively (Table XX).

\textbf{West Coast of Vancouver Island}

To fit the recent age composition and survey data, the model estimates a slow upward trajectory for the stock.
The model fits the most recent spawn survey index (Appendix \ref{chap:input}) and explains the combination of the survey index and the proportions at age data that are dominated by 3 year old fish) as a large recruitment (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2WCVI}).
Natural mortality is very uncertain with an apparent decline in the median estimate but a range of trajectories that include increasing and stable (Figure \ref{figStoryboardAM2WCVI}).
Driven by the estimates recent recruitments and lower natural mortality, the assessment estimates 2014 spawning stock biomass and depletion levels of 30 (18,52) kt and 0.52 (0.31, 0.84) respectively (Table XX).

